    category: 'How Things Work',
    subcategory: 'Digital Payments',
    definition: 'UPI (Unified Payments Interface) is a real-time payment system built by the National Payments Corporation of India (NPCI) that enables instant money transfer between any two bank accounts using a mobile phone. Here is the step-by-step technical flow: Step 1: User opens a UPI-enabled app (Google Pay, PhonePe, Paytm) and enters the recipient\'s UPI ID (e.g., name@bank), scans a QR code, or selects a contact. Step 2: The app creates a payment request and sends it to the UPI platform via the NPCI\'s centralized switch. Step 3: The UPI platform validates the transaction by checking the recipient\'s UPI ID against a mapping database that links UPI IDs to bank accounts. Step 4: The platform sends an authentication request to the user\'s bank (issuer bank) via the Immediate Payment Service (IMPS) infrastructure. Step 5: The user\'s bank prompts the user to enter their UPI PIN (a 4-6 digit personal identification number) to authorize the transaction. Step 6: Once the PIN is verified, the issuer bank debits the amount and sends a confirmation to the UPI platform. Step 7: The UPI platform forwards the debit confirmation to the recipient\'s bank (acquirer bank), which credits the amount to the recipient\'s account in real time. Step 8: Both user and recipient receive instant notifications. The entire process takes 2-5 seconds and operates 24/7, including weekends and holidays, because IMPS has no downtime. UPI uses a two-factor authentication model: the device (phone number linked to the bank account) and the UPI PIN. Each UPI app generates a virtual payment address (VPA) that acts as a proxy for the actual bank account number, ensuring that sensitive bank details are never shared during transactions.',
    simpleExplanation: 'UPI is like sending a digital cheque that clears instantly — you just need the person\'s virtual address (like name@bank) and a secret PIN, and the money moves from your bank to theirs in seconds without ever sharing your account number.',
