    category: 'How Things Work',
    subcategory: 'Artificial Intelligence',
    definition: 'ChatGPT is a large language model (LLM) built by OpenAI that uses a deep learning architecture called the Transformer to generate human-like text. Here is the step-by-step technical process: Step 1: Pretraining — The model was trained on hundreds of billions of words from the internet, books, articles, and code. During training, it learned to predict the next word in a sequence by analyzing patterns across this massive corpus. This is called self-supervised learning because the data itself provides the labels (the next word is the label for the previous words). Step 2: The Transformer architecture uses a mechanism called self-attention, which weighs the importance of every word in the input relative to every other word. For example, in "The cat sat on the mat because it was tired," the model learns that "it" refers to "cat". Attention allows the model to capture long-range dependencies that previous models (like RNNs) struggled with. Step 3: Fine-tuning (RLHF) — After pretraining, OpenAI fine-tuned the model using Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback. Human raters evaluated multiple model outputs for quality, safety, and helpfulness. A reward model was trained based on these ratings, and ChatGPT was optimized to maximize this reward score, aligning the model with human preferences. Step 4: Inference — When you type a prompt, ChatGPT tokenizes your text into subword units (tokens), passes them through the Transformer layers (96 layers in GPT-4), computes attention scores, and generates one token at a time autoregressively. Each new token is selected based on probability distribution over the vocabulary — not always the most likely token, but sampled to maintain creativity. Step 5: Context window — ChatGPT has a limited context window (8K to 128K tokens depending on version) that acts as its "short-Concept memory". Everything in the current conversation stays in this window, which is why long conversations can become expensive and lose early context. The model has no persistent memory across sessions unless explicitly implemented via external systems.',
    simpleExplanation: 'ChatGPT is like a hyper-intelligent text predictor that read most of the internet, learned how humans write and reason, and can now continue any conversation by predicting the most appropriate next words, one at a time.',
