    realCompanyExample: 'Netflix itself is the proof. Starting as a DVD-by-mail company in 1997, it pivoted to streaming in 2007 and invested massively in its recommendation engine. The company now spends $17 billion annually on content, but the recommendation system is what ensures each subscriber finds content they love, making the catalog feel infinite and personalized.',
    visualDiagram: 'Step 1: User interacts with Netflix (watch, rate, search, browse) → Step 2: All interactions logged to data pipeline → Step 3: Batch processing computes user-item interaction matrix → Step 4: Collaborative filtering finds similar users and items → Step 5: Content analysis computes micro-genre tags → Step 6: Deep learning model computes latent preference vectors → Step 7: Ranking service scores all titles for this user → Step 8: Row generator organizes top scores into personalized rows → Step 9: Thumbnail selector picks optimal image per title per user → Step 10: Personalized homepage rendered in under 1 second',
    quickSummary: 'Netflix\'s recommendation engine combines collaborative filtering, content-based analysis with 76,000+ micro-genre tags, deep learning, and contextual signals to personalize every user\'s homepage, driving 80% of watch time and saving over $1 billion annually.',
